        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use ALMA Band 8 to probe the [OIII]88um line and the 0.7 mm continuum from the luminous LAE at z=7.308. We choose a 1875.0 MHz bandwidth with a 7.813 MHz resolution and a spectral averaging of 16 for the [OIII] line (Baseband-1), and a 2000 MHz bandwidth with a 31.250 MHz resolution for the continuum (Baseband-2, 3, and 4), in the dual polarization mode. This will enable us to observe the [OIII] line and the 0.7 mm continuum simultaneously. In order to observe the same spatial resolution as will be used in our approved Band 6 program, we choose a spatial resolution of 0.6 arcsec, which can be accomplished with the array configurations of C34-2 to C34-6 (Table 7.1 of Technical Handbook for ALMA cycle 2). Standard calibrations recommended by the observatory will suffice.

The total star-formation rate of our target estimated from the UV spectrum is 22 Msun/yr. Based on the model calculations by Inoue et al. (2013), expected [OIII]88um flux from the galaxy is estimated to be (1.3-1.7) x 10^(-18) erg/s/cm^2 when Z/Zsun ~= 0.13-1.0 (Figure 1 right in Scientific Justification). Assuming that the velocity width (FWHM) of the line is 100 km/s, we obtain 0.72-0.97 mJy for the [OIII] line peak flux density which requires 0.15 mJy per 100 km/s (rms) for at least ~= 5 sigma detection.

The IR luminosity of this source is estimated from the difference between the SFR estimated from its apparent UV luminosity and the SFR corrected for dust attenuation, 15.3 Msun/yr, to be 8.9 x 10^(10) Lsun (Kennicutt 1998). This in turn gives the 0.7 mm continuum flux density of 0.098 mJy, on the assumption of a modified blackbody SED with a dust temperature of 40 K and an emissivity index of 1.5 (Eales et al. 1989; Klaas et al. 1997). Note that this object has been observed by the Herschel Multi-tiered Extragalactic Survey (HerMES). We confirm that their DR2 UDS images do not show any significant detection at the position of the z=7.308 source. Based on the 5 sigma detection limits of the UDS field, the continuum flux density is estimated to be &lt; 11.2 mJy at 250 um, &lt; 9.3 mJy at 350 um, and &lt; 13.4 mJy at 500 um (Oliver et al. 2012), which are consistent with our estimates of its far-infrared continuum flux density.

According to the ALMA Observing Tool ETC, we require a 18.5-hour observing time including calibration and overhead to achieve ~= 5 sigma detections of the [OIII] line and the 0.7 mm continuum. These estimates are based on fiducial assumptions for high redshift star-forming galaxies, and the successful detections are promising.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
